@mookosh Is it really historical revisionism? The lowest scholarly estimate I've seen used for the Bengal famine is 0.8 million deaths, 800 thousand, whereas contemporary consensus estimates the deaths at 2.1 million.

The government of India were repeatedly warned that exhausting India's supply would lean to a famine, but still kept exporting grain from India to other parts of the empire. This kept going even as India's viceroy continued to beg for emergency wheat supplies. The wheat arrived, eventually, in fractions of the requested quantity that were far too small to properly alleviate the famine. That's not even mentioning how boats and rice supplies were confiscated from Bengal's coast as a part of the war effort, denying the local people their livelihoods, supplies of preexisting food, and ways of getting more food in the future. Meanwhile, imports of Australian what passed India not even to feed starving Europeans, but to be stored for future consumption in Europe. Imports dropped, prices skyrocketed, and scalpers made fortunes whilst insufficient wheat arrived in India to alleviate the famine.

Now ultimately I can't travel back in time and crack open the heads of the British government people at the time to see what really drove them. Their disregard for India, however, can rather succinctly be correlated with what they have said, written, and given speeches about when discussing the Indian people. Many of Churchill's sentiments, like how the native people 'breed like rabbits', can be seen recapitulated in the talking points of racist conservatives to this day. I think it's quite clear that this bigotry, to some extent or another, is going to impact policy.

