@dr.doppeldecker3832 Foreign Policy decisions are driven by things other than the Military Industry.

If you want an example of a country where the Military Industrial Complex had a vast amount of power, the Brezhnev Era Soviet Union is an excellent example. In spite of the simultaneous development and production of 3 different types of Main Battle Tanks with composite armour and 125mm smoothbore main guns (the T-64, T-72 and T-80), in spite of the "Small Civil War" between different factions of the Military and Missile Industry in the late 1960s that led to the simultaneous procurement of the UR-100U, UR-100N and MR-UR-100 "light" ICBMs (all different designs despite their similar designation, not to mention that at the same time the R-36M Heavy ICBM and RT-21 Road Mobile ICBMs were also developed at the same time) and in spite of producing as many 3 or even 4.7 times as many SLBMs as they had missile tubes on submarines that could carry them, the Brezhnev Era Soviet Union did not get into many wars (certainly not as many as the US in the 1990s to the early 2000s with a much smaller amount of defence spending). Indeed Soviet Military Procurement during this period was driven more by internal politics than any external threat, perceived or otherwise, and even when Gorbachev entered, projects were ongoing regardless as to whether they had his approval or not. The US has never  approached this level of system diversity or pointless overproduction. Whilst Soviet Industry could produce systems considerably in excess of the requirements of the Soviet Military, the US Military has considerably reduced requirement over the course of the Cold War.

If a Military Industrial Complex gains too much influence in a country, it does not need to mire that country in Counter-insurgencies to ensure that money is still spent. If a Military Industrial Complex has enough influence, it will ensure that the money spend that money regardless  if the country is at peace.

